<!--
    Demo Case 09 - Resolved / Complaint / High priority
    ====================================================================

    Synthetic seed record for the case-management POC scoped application.
    This file is the NINTH of the 10-case demo dataset; together with
    cases 01 through 08 and case 10, it satisfies the AAP requirement
    (Section 0.7.4) of "at least 10 demo cases across all six statuses
    and both case types," and contributes to the dataset matrix:

        Case 01 - Draft       / General Inquiry / Medium
        Case 02 - Open        / General Inquiry / Medium
        Case 03 - In Progress / General Inquiry / Medium
        Case 04 - Pending     / General Inquiry / Low
        Case 05 - Resolved    / General Inquiry / High
        Case 06 - Closed      / General Inquiry / Medium
        Case 07 - Open        / Complaint       / High
        Case 08 - In Progress / Complaint       / Critical
        Case 09 - Resolved    / Complaint       / High      ## THIS FILE
        Case 10 - Closed      / Complaint       / Critical

    The 10-case dataset thus exercises:
      * Every one of the six statuses (Draft, Open, In Progress, Pending,
        Resolved, Closed)
      * Both case types (General Inquiry and Complaint) across the
        full lifecycle - case 09 is the canonical RESOLVED COMPLAINT,
        the Complaint-flow analog of case 05 (Resolved General Inquiry)
      * All four priorities (Low, Medium, High, Critical) - this case
        contributes to the High bar in the all_cases_by_priority chart
        (alongside case 05 and case 07)

    Lifecycle position - WHY Resolved / Complaint / High is meaningful:
      A Complaint case that has reached Resolved status has traversed
      Draft -> Open -> In Progress -> Resolved (skipping Pending). The
      agent has completed all investigative tasks and is now awaiting
      manager review for final closure. The High priority is appropriate
      at this lifecycle phase: the case had elevated urgency during the
      investigation but has cooled to "resolved-pending-close" and no
      longer carries the Critical priority that case 08 exhibits at the
      In Progress phase.

    Role / cross-dependency context (per AAP Section 0.5.2):

      This case DEPENDS ON (loaded BEFORE this record):
        - The scoped application records under ../../app/
            (sys_app and sys_scope; this case's <sys_scope>/<sys_package>
             reference fields resolve via the source attribute against
             those records)
        - The case table definition at ../../tables/x_casemgmt_case.xml
            (this record's <sys_class_name>x_casemgmt_case</sys_class_name>
             requires the table to exist)
        - All dictionary entries for the case table under
            ../../dictionary/x_casemgmt_case_*.xml  (every populated
            field below requires its dictionary entry to be present)
        - All choice records under ../../choices/  (the type=Complaint,
            status=Resolved, and priority=High choice values must be
            registered)
        - The auto-numbering record at
            ../../numbers/sys_number_x_casemgmt_case.xml  (defines the
            CASE0000001 format; this record's <number/> is intentionally
            absent so the platform auto-generates per that format on
            insert)
        - The role records under ../../roles/  (the demo agent's read
            and write access requires the x_casemgmt_case_agent role and
            its ACLs; the eventual Resolved->Closed transition will
            require the demo manager's x_casemgmt_case_manager role)
        - The ACL records under ../../acl/  (table-level and field-level
            ACLs gate read/write access; the demo agent reads/writes
            this case via the "Assigned only" clause of the agent ACLs)
        - The business rule records under ../../business_rules/
            (set_opened_date Before-Insert auto-sets <opened_date> on
             this case at import time; block_draft_backtransition will
             prevent any Resolved->Draft attempt; set_closed_date will
             fire only on a future Resolved->Closed transition - NOT on
             this insert)
        - The flow records under ../../flows/
            (../../flows/complaint_state_machine.xml governs this case;
             it is the COMPLAINT-flow analog of case 05's general_inquiry
             flow - the canonical RESOLVE-SUCCESS test for the complaint
             flow)
        - ../users/sys_user_x_casemgmt_demo_agent.xml  (referenced by
            <assigned_agent>; resolved by user_name lookup)
        - ../groups/sys_user_group_x_casemgmt_demo_team.xml  (referenced
            by <assigned_group>; resolved by name lookup)
        - ../role_assignments/sys_user_has_role_x_casemgmt_demo_agent.xml
            (grants the case_agent role to the demo agent so the agent
            can read/write this case via the "Assigned only" ACL clause)

      This case IS REFERENCED BY (loaded AFTER this record):
        - ../tasks/x_casemgmt_case_task_demo_*.xml - specifically the
            single Closed task per the seed script's task table:
            "Demo task 08: Final complaint review" (status = Closed,
            due_date = -2 days from today). With this single Closed task
            and ZERO non-Closed tasks, the validate_resolved_transition
            subflow's GlideRecord query against x_casemgmt_case_task where
            case=current AND status!=Closed returns ZERO rows, allowing
            the In Progress -> Resolved transition to succeed. This is
            the inverse of case 08 (which is BLOCKED by non-Closed tasks).
        - ../parties/x_casemgmt_case_party_demo_*.xml - specifically the
            Person-type Witness party (referencing the demo agent). This
            exercises the polymorphic UI Policy on the Person side for
            the Complaint flow path.
        - The all_cases_by_status Manager View bar chart at
            ../../reports/x_casemgmt_all_cases_by_status.xml  (this case
            populates the Resolved bar)
        - The all_cases_by_type Manager View donut at
            ../../reports/x_casemgmt_all_cases_by_type.xml  (this case
            populates the Complaint slice)
        - The all_cases_by_priority Manager View bar chart at
            ../../reports/x_casemgmt_all_cases_by_priority.xml  (this
            case populates one of the High entries; case 05 and case 07
            are the others)
        - The case_count_by_status Agent Workspace donut at
            ../../reports/x_casemgmt_case_count_by_status.xml  (this case
            populates the Resolved slice)
        - The cases_opened_30d Manager View single-score widget at
            ../../reports/x_casemgmt_cases_opened_30d.xml  (since
            opened_date is auto-set to "now" by the set_opened_date
            business rule at insert time, this case is included in the
            count of cases opened within the last 30 days)
        - The avg_time_to_close Manager View single-score widget at
            ../../reports/x_casemgmt_avg_time_to_close.xml  (this case
            does NOT contribute because the widget filters on
            status=Closed and this case is Resolved, not Closed; only
            cases 06 and 10 contribute to the average)
        - The validate_resolved_transition subflow test in Validation
            Gate 2 (RESOLVE-SUCCESS): THIS CASE IS THE CANONICAL
            RESOLVE-SUCCESS TEST FOR THE COMPLAINT FLOW. Where case 05
            tests resolve-success in the general_inquiry flow, this case
            tests it in the complaint flow. Both flows MUST behave
            identically when all child tasks are Closed.
        - The validate_closed_transition subflow test in Validation
            Gate 2 (CLOSE-SUCCESS on COMPLAINT): a case_manager-roled
            user (the demo manager) can close this case via the form,
            demonstrating that the complaint flow's
            validate_closed_transition subflow checks the manager role
            and allows the transition. The set_closed_date Before-Update
            business rule will fire on that subsequent update and
            populate closed_date to gs.nowDateTime().
        - The Agent Workspace's "My Open Cases" list at
            ../../reports/x_casemgmt_my_open_cases.xml does NOT include
            this case: the list filter excludes Resolved (and Closed)
            cases per "status NOT IN (Resolved, Closed)".

    Authoring rules honored (per AAP Sections 0.7.1 / 0.7.2 and the
    agent prompt's ten authoring rules):

      Rule 1 - Synthetic only (AAP Section 0.7.2 NO-PII clause):
        subject       = "Demo case 09: Resolved (Complaint)"
        description   = "Synthetic Resolved complaint case awaiting
                         manager close." (no PII; the wording emphasizes
                         the lifecycle position - resolved by agent,
                         awaiting manager review for closure)
        requester_name  = "Synthetic Requester Nine" (synthetic
                          identifier using the literal word "Synthetic"
                          plus a numeral spelled out for the requester,
                          NOT a real person's name)
        requester_email = "requester-9@example.invalid"
                          (RFC 2606 / BCP 32 reserved .invalid TLD never
                          resolves to a real domain; the local part uses
                          the NUMERAL "9" matching the file numbering -
                          consistent with the other 9 case files'
                          NUMERAL convention for the email local part
                          versus the SPELLED-OUT word for the
                          requester_name field)

      Rule 2 - No auto-number override:
        The <number/> element is intentionally absent. The auto-number
        engine defined in ../../numbers/sys_number_x_casemgmt_case.xml
        generates a CASE0000001-format value on insert per AAP Section
        0.5.7 (the "number" row of the case schema specifies "Auto-
        number" with format CASE0000001 and Read-only constraint).

      Rule 3 - Auto-set opened_date (NO explicit override):
        The <opened_date/> element is intentionally absent. The
        set_opened_date Before-Insert business rule at
        ../../business_rules/x_casemgmt_set_opened_date.xml fires on
        insert and sets opened_date = gs.nowDateTime(). This means the
        case will appear as "opened today" at import time, which is
        appropriate for the cases_opened_30d widget (this case is
        included in the 30-day count). Unlike case 10 (Closed) and case
        06 (Closed General Inquiry), this case does NOT need an explicit
        opened_date override because:
          * It is NOT used to compute avg_time_to_close (which excludes
            non-Closed cases).
          * It IS appropriate for the case to appear "fresh" in the
            cases_opened_30d count (a Resolved-but-not-yet-Closed case
            is still recently active).

      Rule 4 - No closed_date in Resolved (NO explicit override, NO BR
               fire either):
        The <closed_date/> element is intentionally absent. Per AAP
        Section 0.5.5 the set_closed_date business rule fires only on
        Resolved -> Closed update, NOT on direct insert with status =
        Resolved. So closed_date remains null after insert - which is
        correct for a Resolved (not yet Closed) case. The
        avg_time_to_close report filters on status=Closed and ignores
        null closed_date values, so this case correctly does NOT appear
        in that widget.

      Rule 5 - Both assignments populated, NO pending_reason:
        assigned_group = "x_casemgmt_demo_team"  (mandatory because the
                         case had to traverse Open -> ... -> Resolved,
                         and assigned_group is required at Open per
                         AAP Section 0.5.5; the value persists through
                         all subsequent statuses)
        assigned_agent = "x_casemgmt_demo_agent"  (mandatory because the
                         case had to traverse In Progress -> ... ->
                         Resolved, and assigned_agent is required at In
                         Progress per AAP Section 0.5.5; the value
                         persists; the agent is also a member of
                         x_casemgmt_demo_team per the seed script's
                         group-membership creation, satisfying the
                         validate_assigned_agent_membership business
                         rule's pre-update guard)
        pending_reason = (absent / unpopulated)  (Resolved cases never
                         carry a pending_reason; if the case ever
                         transitioned through Pending, the
                         clear_pending_reason_on_inprogress business
                         rule would have cleared the value when the
                         case left Pending; this case did NOT traverse
                         Pending, so the value was never set)

      Rule 6 - Choice value precision:
        type     = "Complaint"  (exactly as registered in
                   ../../choices/sys_choice_case_type.xml; the second
                   of the two case types; capital C deliberate)
        status   = "Resolved"   (exactly as registered in
                   ../../choices/sys_choice_case_status.xml; the
                   penultimate state before terminal Closed; capital R
                   deliberate - "Resolved" not "resolved" or "RESOLVED")
        priority = "High"       (exactly as registered in
                   ../../choices/sys_choice_case_priority.xml; capital
                   H deliberate - "High" not "high" or "HIGH")

      Rule 7 - Zero hardcoded sys_id cross-references (AAP Section
               0.7.2 "NO sys_id literals anywhere"):
        The case's OWN <sys_id> below is the record's primary key,
        which is acceptable per the AAP rule (it is NOT a reference to
        any other record). It is a deterministic 32-character lowercase
        hex value computed at file generation time as the MD5 of the
        idempotent subject "Demo case 09: Resolved (Complaint)" =
        de01d9646c4aaf849d0aec60c6c32368 - so the Update Set engine
        resolves the same sys_id on every PDI import, making the record
        idempotent.

        EVERY cross-reference field below uses the stable human-readable
        lookup key (user_name / name / scope source) as both the
        display_value attribute AND the text content - NOT a hardcoded
        sys_id literal. This matches the convention established by every
        peer file in the scoped Update Set (sys_user_*, sys_user_group_*,
        sys_user_has_role_*, dictionary/x_casemgmt_*, case 10, etc.) and
        complies with the AAP Section 0.7.2 "NO sys_id literals
        anywhere" rule:
          - <assigned_agent display_value="x_casemgmt_demo_agent">
                x_casemgmt_demo_agent
            </assigned_agent>  resolves by user_name lookup
          - <assigned_group display_value="x_casemgmt_demo_team">
                x_casemgmt_demo_team
            </assigned_group>  resolves by name lookup
          - <sys_scope display_value="Case Management">x_casemgmt</sys_scope>
                resolves by scope source-name lookup
          - <sys_package display_value="Case Management" source="x_casemgmt">
                x_casemgmt
            </sys_package>  resolves by scope source-name lookup

      Rule 8 - Scope binding:
        <sys_scope>   binds this case row to the scoped application via
                      the scope source name "x_casemgmt" defined in
                      ../../app/sys_scope/x_casemgmt.xml at
                      <source>x_casemgmt</source>; the display_value
                      "Case Management" matches the sys_app's human-
                      readable name.
        <sys_package> follows the same pattern with the additional
                      source="x_casemgmt" attribute that is required by
                      the Update Set engine for scope-package binding.
        Note: the source attribute value "x_casemgmt" matches what every
        peer file uses; it is the scope's <source> field, NOT the
        scoped application's sys_update_name. This is the convention
        used consistently across the project's Update Set artifacts
        (case 10, all sys_user_*, sys_user_group_*, sys_user_has_role_*
        records use the same convention).

      Rule 9 - Idempotency anchor:
        The case's idempotent key is <subject> =
        "Demo case 09: Resolved (Complaint)". The companion seed script
        ../../scripts/seed_demo_data.js ensureCase() helper queries
        x_casemgmt_case by subject BEFORE inserting; the
        action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE" attribute on the inner <x_casemgmt_case>
        element ensures the same behavior at Update Set import time.
        Both the action attribute and the deterministic sys_id make
        re-imports on a fresh PDI byte-identical and collision-free.

      Rule 10 - Scoped Update Set XML conventions:
        Root element:  <record_update table="x_casemgmt_case">
        Inner element: <x_casemgmt_case action="INSERT_OR_UPDATE"> for
                       idempotent re-import per AAP Section 0.7.1
                       round-trip-verification gate (Validation Gate 7).
        UTF-8 encoding declared in XML prolog.
        Element ordering: alphabetical (matching the established peer
        convention used by sys_user_*, sys_user_group_*,
        sys_user_has_role_*, role records, case 10, and dictionary
        entries across the scoped Update Set).
        Unix-style line endings (LF) per AAP file authoring conventions.

    Source-side semantic reference (read-only, NOT byte-for-byte ported)
    per AAP Section 0.8.1:
      acm-plugins/acm-default-plugins/acm-case-file-plugin/src/main/java/
        com/armedia/acm/plugins/casefile/model/CaseFile.java
        ArkCase's CaseFile JPA entity declares ~80 fields including
        cm_case_status (the source for our <status>), cm_case_priority
        (the source for our <priority>), cm_case_type (the source for
        our <type>), cm_case_title (the source for our <subject>),
        cm_case_details (Lob; the source for our <description>), and
        cm_case_closed (Temporal TIMESTAMP; the source for our
        <closed_date>). The ServiceNow target collapses ArkCase's ~80
        fields to the user-prompt's 12-field schema (number, type,
        status, priority, subject, description, opened_date, closed_date,
        assigned_group, assigned_agent, requester_name, requester_email
        - plus the optional pending_reason). ArkCase's queue-handler-
        driven default status flow ("DRAFT" -> "ACTIVE" on save via
        CaseFileQueueHandler.java) is replaced in this POC by Flow
        Designer's complaint_state_machine.xml; ArkCase's
        ChangeCaseFileStateService.java is replaced by the
        x_casemgmt_CaseTransitionValidator script include.

    Validation hooks (per the agent prompt):
      - The XML well-formedness check (xmllint with no-output flag)
        returns zero errors.
      - No-PII grep returns zero matches against (john|jane|smith|doe|
        @gmail|@yahoo|@outlook|@hotmail|\.com|\.org|\.net) - the
